sec.p:
The diameter of the FAST reflector is 500 m; the fully illuminated aperture at any time is D = 300 m since the telescope is designed to track objects. The beam size of the FAST is given by
(1)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
\theta &=& 1.22 \times \frac{21\, {\rm cm}(1+z)}{300 \, {\rm m}}= 2.94 (1+z) \, {\rm arcmin}
\end{eqnarray*}$$for observation of the 21-cm line from redshift $z$.

The sky drifts across with a speed of ωecos δ in a drift scan survey, where $\omega _\mathrm{ e} \approx 0.25 \, {\rm arcmin}/\mathrm{ s}$ is the angular velocity of the rotation of the Earth, and δ is the declination of the pointing. The time for drifting across a pixel is given by
(2)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
t_{\rm pix}&=& 2.9(1+z) \, {\rm arcmin}/(\omega _\mathrm{ e} \cos \delta).
\end{eqnarray*}$$One circle is completed in a sidereal day, though in practice the night time data are usually of much smaller noise than the day time data. At $z$ = 0, and cos δ ≈ 1/2 (near the zenith of FAST site), we get 24 s per beam. And because of the overlap of 19 beams in one horizontal scanning (see Fig. 1), most pixels in a 19-beam strip will be scanned twice, resulting in 48 s per beam. Within the observable part of sky, the circles with higher declination (northern part of sky) have smaller area, while the integration time per pixel is larger. The expected thermal noise for a dual polarization single beam is
(3)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
\sigma _{\rm noise} = \sqrt{2}\frac{k_\mathrm{ B} T_{\rm sys}}{A_{\rm eff}}\frac{1}{\sqrt{\Delta \nu t}} ,
\end{eqnarray*}$$where t is the total integration time, Δν is the frequency bandwidth for a channel, and kB the Boltzmann constant. The aperture efficiency is about 70 $\rm { per\, cent}$, giving effective aperture Aeff ≈ 50 000 $\, {\rm m}^2$. The system temperature is Tsys = Trec + Tsky, where Trec is the receiver temperature and taken to be 20 K, and away from the Galactic plane, the sky temperature is modelled as
(4)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
T_{\rm sky} = 2.73 + 25.2 \times (0.408/\nu _{\rm GHz})^{2.75} K.
\end{eqnarray*}$$

In the case of 19-beam L-band feed, approximately every pixel would be covered by several beams, effectively double the integration time. In a more careful treatment, we may estimate the noise as follows. The time stream data are related to the signal by
(5)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf {\mathit{ d}={A s} + n},
\end{eqnarray*}$$where the time-ordered data vector $\mathbf {\mathit{ d}}$ has a dimension of 19Nt where Nt is the length of the time-ordered data, the sky pixel vector $\mathbf {\mathit{ s}}$ has a dimension Npix, and the pointing matrix $\mathbf {A}$ has a dimension of 19Nt × Npix. The minimum variance estimator for the sky is
(6)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf { \hat{s} = (A^t N^{-1} A)^{-1} A^{t} N^{-1} s} ,
\end{eqnarray*}$$where $\mathbf {N}$ is the covariance matrix of the noise in the time-ordered data. The sky map noise covariance matrix is then
(7)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
\mathbf {C_{N} = (A^{T}N^{-1}A)^{-1}}.
\end{eqnarray*}$$Using this expression, we can estimate the map noise.

For intensity mapping survey, the measurement error of the power spectrum can be written as (Seo et al. 2010)
(17)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{\sigma _{P}}{P} & = & 2\pi \sqrt{\frac{1}{V_{\rm eff}(k)k^2\Delta k}},
\end{eqnarray*}$$with the Veff given in this case by
(18)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
V_{\rm eff}(\vec{k}) = V_{\rm sur}\left(1+\frac{\sigma _{\rm pix}^2V_{\rm pix}}{[\bar{S}(z)]W(\vec{k})^2P}+\frac{1/{\bar{n}}}{P}\right)^{-2},
\end{eqnarray*}$$where $\bar{S}(z)$ is the average 21-cm emission flux density and Vpix is the pixel volume. The first term is due to sample variance, the second term is induced by the system thermal noise, and the last term is the shot noise due to the discreteness of the H i sources, with $1/{\bar{n}} \approx$ 100$\mathrm{ h}^{-3}\, {\rm Mpc}^3$ [Seo et al. (2010)]. We model the angular resolution (the frequency resolution is much higher) as:
(19)$$\begin{eqnarray*}
W(k) = \exp \bigg [-\frac{1}{2}k^2r(z)^2\bigg (\frac{\theta _{\rm pix}(z)}{2\sqrt{2\ln {2}}}\bigg)^2\bigg ] .
\end{eqnarray*}$$

